<h3 id="finding-anomalies-in-china-kewen-hou-fang-qiao-xiaoyuan-zhang-2021">Finding Anomalies in China, KeWen Hou, Fang Qiao, Xiaoyuan Zhang (2021)</h3>

<h4 id="æ¦‚è¿°">æ¦‚è¿°</h4>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
    <li>the Chinese stock market differs from the U.S. stock market in two important
aspects: <font color="red">trading environment</font> 
and <font color="red">information environment</font>.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
    <li>After risk adjustment, we find that 97 CAPM alphas are significant,
16 CH3 alphas are significant and 15 CH4 alphas are significant.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
    <li>The CAPM alphas are very similar to the raw return, indicating that 
the market risk fails to explain these anomaly returns.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
    <li>In contrast, with embedded size, value and turnover effects, the
CH3 and CH4 models are able to explain away a significant part of anomaly
raw returns, and thus we foucs our discussion on alphas using this model.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
    <li>Among the 16 significant alphas relative to CH3 factors, 7 anomalies are 
constructed using liquidity-related information, and 4 are related to 
accounting-related information.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
    <li>Among the 15 significant alphas relative to the CH4 factors, 
half of anomalies are from trading-related information and half of them 
are from accounting-related information.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
    <li></li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

